1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,040
Criminal networks, how much they actually earn.

2
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:06,700
This is the title and the heart of our in-depth study today.

3
00:00:06,700 --> 00:00:12,320
And believe me, it looks like the beginning of a crime film, but in reality we are about to dive into

4
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:15,120
a real economic detective story.

5
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:20,080
A fascinating journey that will lead us to uncover the secret bank accounts of the

6
00:00:20,080 --> 00:00:22,080
Italian-American mafia of the 1960s.

7
00:00:22,080 --> 00:00:27,000
And I assure you that what we will soon discover will completely overturn the way

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,359
we think about power and the real value of our contacts.

9
00:00:30,359 --> 00:00:33,039
Okay, let's get right into it.

10
00:00:33,039 --> 00:00:34,359
Try to think about it.

11
00:00:34,359 --> 00:00:38,759
How does an economist measure the invisible wealth of a secret society?

12
00:00:38,759 --> 00:00:43,600
I mean, we are talking about criminals who, obviously, certainly didn't fill out their

13
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:46,079
income tax returns for their illegal activities, right?

14
00:00:46,079 --> 00:00:52,879
Calculating the profits of a mafia boss in 1960 literally seems like an impossible mission,

15
00:00:52,879 --> 00:00:55,000
one of those investigations with no way out.

16
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:59,560
But this is exactly where economic science becomes, I dare say, brilliant.

17
00:00:59,560 --> 00:01:04,200
But let's stop for a second for an absolutely crucial clarification.

18
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:09,200
We are not talking about bar gossip or the plot of the latest TV series.

19
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:13,840
Everything we will see is based on a very rigorous and peer-reviewed

20
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:18,400
scientific study, published by a prestigious institution like the Royal Economic

21
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:19,400
Society.

22
00:01:19,400 --> 00:01:23,640
The author, economist Giovanni Mastrobuoni, applied pure analytical methods to

23
00:01:23,640 --> 00:01:29,040
reveal the hidden economy of organized crime, so foundations as solid as a rock.

24
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:33,739
Now, to perform this kind of statistical magic, the study got its hands on an absolute

25
00:01:33,739 --> 00:01:39,480
gold mine: 800 top-secret files from the U.S. Federal Bureau of Narcotics,

26
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:41,439
declassified only recently.

27
00:01:41,439 --> 00:01:46,439
We are in 1960, a key moment, just before the government really started

28
00:01:46,439 --> 00:01:48,240
getting serious with the raids.

29
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:52,680
These files map out with precision the network of 800 mobsters, including heavyweights like

30
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:53,680
Joe Bonanno.

31
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:57,560
In short, it's as if we suddenly had the secret phone book of the entire

32
00:01:57,560 --> 00:01:58,560
underworld.

33
00:01:58,560 --> 00:02:03,360
And this map shoves rule number one of the Cosa Nostra handbook in our faces.

34
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:07,800
In the world of the mafia, forget about being able to simply approach a guy and shake

35
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:08,800
his hand.

36
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:13,800
Direct introductions are strictly forbidden; an intermediary is always needed, someone

37
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,760
who is blindly trusted.

38
00:02:15,760 --> 00:02:20,680
This makes us understand that, in this dark environment, knowing who knows who is not a small

39
00:02:20,680 --> 00:02:25,599
detail, it is literally a matter of life or death and, above all, of control.

40
00:02:25,599 --> 00:02:31,480
And this is where mathematical analysis comes into play, with a key concept called closeness

41
00:02:31,480 --> 00:02:32,480
centrality.

42
00:02:32,480 --> 00:02:37,760
In simple terms, what is the average distance between a mobster and any other person

43
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:38,760
in the organization.

44
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:43,500
In a world where, as we've just seen, guarantors are always needed, being very

45
00:02:43,500 --> 00:02:48,159
close to everyone means needing very few steps to reach those who matter.

46
00:02:48,159 --> 00:02:52,039
Whoever has this type of centrality moves the pieces much faster than others.

47
00:02:52,039 --> 00:02:56,439
But there is also another side of the coin: betweenness centrality.

48
00:02:56,439 --> 00:03:01,759
How many times a specific person acts as a vital bridge between two groups that otherwise

49
00:03:01,759 --> 00:03:05,400
would never speak to each other; imagine a boss who is the only connection between

50
00:03:05,400 --> 00:03:09,319
two isolated mafia families; he has incredible monopoly power.

51
00:03:09,319 --> 00:03:12,639
If you remove him, the system goes haywire and business grinds to a halt.

52
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:16,000
But at this point, the study hits a massive wall.

53
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,680
What statisticians call reverse causality.

54
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:25,120
In short, which came first, the chicken or the egg: is a mobster wealthy because he was great

55
00:03:25,120 --> 00:03:29,599
at making the right friends, or does he have all those friends just because he was already filthy rich

56
00:03:29,599 --> 00:03:32,360
and literally bought them?

57
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:35,680
If we don't solve this enigma, the data is worthless.

58
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:39,280
And here is the economist's first real stroke of genius.

59
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:44,439
Since illegal bank accounts are by definition invisible, he used an indicator

60
00:03:44,439 --> 00:03:49,800
that cannot be hidden: bricks and mortar, the real estate market. He took the exact

61
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:55,680
addresses of the houses these mobsters lived in in 1960 and entered them into the database

62
00:03:55,680 --> 00:04:00,840
of the famous real estate portal Zillow to estimate how much those properties were actually worth.

63
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:05,240
Sure, you might be wondering, you can't take the price of a villa today to understand

64
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:11,560
how rich someone was in 1960; quite right. In fact, after collecting current estimates,

65
00:04:11,560 --> 00:04:14,000
the prices were mathematically deflated.

66
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:17,639
They were cross-referenced with historical census data from that time,

67
00:04:17,639 --> 00:04:23,519
metropolitan area by metropolitan area, bringing them back to the exact purchasing power of 1960.

68
00:04:23,519 --> 00:04:24,519
The result?

69
00:04:24,519 --> 00:04:28,519
A surgical and objective estimate of the bosses' portfolio.

70
00:04:28,519 --> 00:04:33,600
Okay, now we have the house values, but let's go back to our big problem from before.

71
00:04:33,600 --> 00:04:38,319
How do we prove beyond any reasonable doubt that it was the connections

72
00:04:38,319 --> 00:04:40,639
that generated the money and not the other way around?

73
00:04:40,639 --> 00:04:47,159
How do we isolate the pure value of networking, without the calculations being tainted by initial wealth?

74
00:04:47,159 --> 00:04:53,439
Drum roll, and here is the second incredible find of this research: isonymy.

75
00:04:53,439 --> 00:04:58,719
A difficult word for what is actually a very simple concept: the geography of surnames.

76
00:04:58,719 --> 00:05:02,240
The author went through old Italian phone books to track down

77
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:06,479
exactly which municipality the surnames of these Italian-American criminals came from.

78
00:05:06,479 --> 00:05:09,719
And believe me, this detail is a game-changer.

79
00:05:09,800 --> 00:05:12,000
The reasoning is as smooth as silk.

80
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,600
If you trace a boss's surname in New York and discover that he and another associate historically come

81
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:21,640
from the exact same remote village in Sicily, bingo.

82
00:02:1,640 --> 00:05:26,720
It is almost certain they shared innate ties, of kinship or trust, well before setting

83
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:28,000
foot in America.

84
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,600
By isolating these historical connections, the study created a pure variable,

85
00:05:31,600 --> 00:05:36,680
that has absolutely nothing to do with the money they would make decades later in Chicago or Manhattan.

86
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:40,600
And hold on tight because using this purified mathematical model,

87
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:46,040
the study gives us a jaw-dropping number: 75%.

88
00:05:46,040 --> 00:05:50,920
A tiny increase in a mobster's closeness centrality caused the value

89
00:05:50,920 --> 00:05:53,680
of his house to skyrocket by up to 75% more.

90
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:57,439
We are talking about a literally frightening jump in economic status.

91
00:05:57,439 --> 00:05:59,439
In short, there is no escape.

92
00:05:59,439 --> 00:06:01,079
The math is clear.

93
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:06,959
Being at the center of the criminal network directly causes an explosion of wealth.

94
00:06:06,959 --> 00:06:11,439
It wasn't money buying friends, but the efficiency of one's network of contacts

95
00:06:11,439 --> 00:06:14,240
generating mountains of dirty dollars.

96
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:19,199
In this underground ecosystem, friendships and trust are without a shadow of a doubt

97
00:06:19,199 --> 00:06:20,799
the most precious capital.

98
00:06:20,799 --> 00:06:23,519
At this point, it would be natural to put two and two together.

99
00:06:23,519 --> 00:06:29,399
If the more connected you are, the richer you are, the boss of bosses must live in a solid gold palace, right?

100
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:31,840
But no, here comes the twist.

101
00:06:31,840 --> 00:06:35,880
There is a shocking paradox concerning the very brains of the organization,

102
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:39,160
those supreme leaders with the highest betweenness power.

103
00:06:39,160 --> 00:06:40,840
Take a look at this table:

104
00:06:40,840 --> 00:06:43,960
the supreme leaders, that tiny 9% at the top,

105
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:50,200
had enormous betweenness power compared to the small fry, almost three versus less than two.

106
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:51,880
They were the absolute masters.

107
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:58,280
Yet the average value of their houses was significantly lower than that of their own soldiers.

108
00:06:58,320 --> 00:07:03,880
$362,000 for the top bosses, compared to over $380,000 for the underlings.

109
00:07:03,880 --> 00:07:06,240
But how is something like this possible?

110
00:07:06,240 --> 00:07:08,960
Well, the experts' answer is fascinating.

111
00:07:08,960 --> 00:07:12,360
They call it the attention avoidance strategy.

112
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:16,360
High-level bosses, especially those of the old Sicilian school,

113
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:20,240
deliberately chose to keep a very low profile.

114
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:25,240
They lived in modest houses with no frills so as not to attract the FBI spotlight.

115
00:07:25,280 --> 00:07:29,800
They knew very well that flaunting money would have destroyed their true treasure:

116
00:07:29,800 --> 00:07:35,879
that invisible network of power and secrets that money alone could never buy.

117
00:07:35,879 --> 00:07:40,519
And this brings us to the end of our journey, leaving us with a nagging question in our minds.

118
00:07:40,519 --> 00:07:46,600
We have just seen how invisible networks could increase wealth by 75% in the criminal world,

119
00:07:46,600 --> 00:07:48,600
to the point that they had to be hidden.

120
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:53,360
The real question is, in our world, the everyday legal and transparent one:

121
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:57,680
how much of our success is secretly driven by connections, knowledge,

122
00:07:57,680 --> 00:08:00,400
and trust networks that we take totally for granted?

123
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:04,319
Often, the strongest infrastructure of power is precisely the one you can't see.

124
00:08:04,319 --> 00:08:07,520
Thank you for following us in this analysis and see you next time.